		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64187466" name="comment_link_64187466" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23204090&amp;cid=64187466" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64187466)" >"Environmental Toxin"?</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64187466" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64187466); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~uncqual">uncqual</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~uncqual">( 836337 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64187466">		
		on Thursday January 25, 2024 @11:40AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23204090&amp;cid=64187466">#64187466</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64187466"><p>The claim that NYC designated Social Media as an "Environmental Toxin" seems, from a quick scan of the <i> <a href="https://www.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/notice/2023/coh-advisory-social-media.pdf" title="nyc.gov">advisory</a> [nyc.gov] </i> release from the NYC Commissioner of Health and Mental Hygiene, to be hyperbolic. The words "toxin", "environment", and "environmental" don't appear anywhere in the release nor does it seem to imply any such thing.</p></div>
	</div>

